Introduction¶

Google Symptoms is a new symptom search dataset provided by Google, reporting normalized per-capita search topic popularity. Google maps all search queries to 422 symptoms either COVID-19 related or not. Delphi has already released multiple signals based on "Anosmia" and "Ageusia" search popularities to the public. Though useful, they have extremely low geographical coverage which causes the problem in supporting forecasting work. In this DAP, we are eager to explore more COVID-19 related symptoms and create new indicators that can maintain the same level of predictive power but obtain better geographical coverage. These indicators will be created either based on 6 non-overlapping symptom sets which contain only a small proportion of symptom terms or based on all of the COVID-related symptoms.

We adopted the recommendation made in Addison's report under "Our recommendation" for the Indicator Heterogeneity I: Regression Models DAP to use a blend of static sensorization method for indicator correction which is explained in details in the Sensorization section. The Google symptoms dataset we used was updated on 12-14-2020, the most recent data in this dataset is for 12-08-2020. The target data we used for both correlation analysis and predictive power analysis are smoothed confirmed case incidence rates provided by USA-Facts with as_of date = 2020-12-14.

Methods¶

  • Selection of Symptom Sets
  • Combination of COVID related symptoms
  • Missingness
  • Sensorization
    • Based on raw sum of symptoms within symptom sets
    • Based on regression

Selection of Symptom Sets¶

We are provided with 422 Google search symptoms in total without mapping information from the raw search queries to the symptoms. In order to create a limited number of COVID indicators, we filtered COVID-related symptoms according to symptom terms highlighted by CDC and electronic heath records offered by Nigan (here) and divided them into 6 non-overlapping symptom sets (here). We will try to develop 6 indicators based on the symptoms sets listed below.

Missingness¶

The NAs existing in the Google Symptoms search dataset are not filled randomly. Instead, they represent extremely low popularity which means the daily search volume of the symptom term for a given region does not meet the quality or privacy thresholds. We adopted two methods to deal with missingness before computing the smoothed version using a 7-day moving average for each selected symptoms:

  • 1) fill0: simply fill 0s in;
  • 2) fillminratio: where we assume that the county's missing value was 1/2 of what the minimum county in that state was in terms of its ratio relative to a historical average. In this method, we first computed the ratio for every county (c) in a certain state (s) for a certain date (t): $$Y_c = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^t Y_{c, t}}{t}$$ $$r_{c, t} =\frac{ Y_{c, t} }{ Y_c}$$ where $Y_{c}$is historical average computed based on raw values in county c from the first date (2020-02-20) to date t while $Y_{c, t}$ is the raw value for a county c on date t, $r_{c, t}$ is the computed ratio. Then, we found the smallest ratio for state (s) and for each date (t) which is named to be $rmin_{s, t}$. Finally, the missed values will be filled with $$Y_{c, t} = Y_{c} \times \frac{1}{2} \times rmin_{s, t}$$ Notice that, this method will help counties with some dates available but won't help with counties with no data available at all.

The violin plots below show the proportion of dates that is available for each symptom term overall locations and the comparison between the raw dataset and the dataset with fillminratio method conducted. By comparing the difference of cumulative proportion above the 80% dashed line, we can see that the fillminratio method helps push counties above line 0 (have some dates available) to line 1 (have all dates available). But it has nothing to do with counties having no data available at all (counties at line 0 will stay at line 0). In general, these two methods provide a starting point for smoothing.

Sensorization¶

Here we use a blend of static sensorization as recommended in Addison's report under "Our recommendation" for the Indicator Heterogeneity I DAP. For each date t, we ignore the possibility of temporal heterogeneity and learn a single linear relationship between the indicator and the target for each location. To be more specific, for each date (t) and each location (c), we train the linear regression model based on data from the first date (2020-02-20) to 7 days ago (t-7)

$$y_{tc} \sim x_{tc} \Longrightarrow \text{Model}(tc)$$

and use the coefficient and intercept returned by the linear regression model to make predictions of all the dates on/before t.

$$\tilde{x}_{sc} = \text{predict}(x_{sc}, \text{Model}(tc))$$

where $1 \le s \le t$

Here we reduce the influence of backfilling problem of the target data by removing the most recent 7 days from the training dataset. The earliest as of date that is allowed in COVIDcast API for USA-Facts confirmed_7dav_incidence_prop signal is 2020-06-26. However, we won't get all the data starting from the first date unless we use as of date later than 2020-07-09. Therefore, we manually set the as of date of date on/before data t to be the earliest as of date that guarantees all the dates on/before date t are available. Usually, the as of date will be 2-4 days after date t. Since currently the Google symptoms dataset is updated by Google randomly but will have the daily updates in the future, temporarily we roughly assume that the as of date of Google Symptoms matches with the that of the target data, since we are promised to have 2-5 days' lag in the future. This helps us to better simulate the actual situation. Notice that, We don't control the intercept to be 0 since a 0 popularity of a symptom isn't necessarily equal to 0 case rates.

We use two methods to combine multiple symptoms within different symptom sets:

  • rawsum: simply sum up the popularity of symptoms considered within a symptom set. Note that, this step is conducted before sensorization and the values used are exactly the raw values from the dataset provided by Google.

    To the more specific, for each date t and county c, we will have $$v_{c, t, i} = \sum_{k \in \text{symptom set i}}Y_{c, t, k}$$ where $Y_{c, t, k}$ is the smoothed value for a county c on date t for symptom k, $v_{c, t, i}$ is the value we will get using rawsum for a county c on date t for symptom set i.

  • regression: train multiple symptoms as features in sensorization. Though Google has already normalized the dataset by regional population (search users) and scaled the dataset using the maximum popularity over all the symptoms in a specific location, we do another min-max scaling for each symptom before fitting the linear regression models. This because we usually have some of the symptoms in certain symptoms set with large scales than others which makes it difficult to compare the unit of coefficients corresponding to multiple symptoms.

    To the more specific, for each date t and county c, we will have $$v_{c, t, i} = \sum_{k \in \text{symptom set i}}\text{coef}_{c, t, k} \times \text{minmax}(Y_{c, t, k}) + \text{intercept}_{c, t, i}$$ where for a county c on date t, $Y_{c, t, k}$ is the smoothed value for symptom k, $\text{coef}_{c, t, k}$ is the corresponding coefficient for symptom k, $\text{intercept}_{c, t, i}$ is the intercept returned by the regression model for symptom set i, $v_{c, t, i}$ is the value we will get using regression for symptom set i.

For both of the two methods, the list of counties considered for a specific symptom set is determined by the symptom with the largest number of available counties. For counties that are not available for a specific symptom but are included in the list of counties considered for the corresponding symptom set, the daily popularities are filled with 0s.

  • Time-wise correlations

  • Coefficients and Intercepts

Geographical Coverage¶

Either from the violin plots shown above or from the bar plots shown below, it can be seen that the number of counties with > 50% days available remains constant among different symptom sets no matter which method is used to fill missingness or combine multiple symptoms. The geographical coverages are similar for all the symptom sets except for Sensory, which has only ~100 counties available, and Pain, which has ~2600 counties available. There are ~1400 counties covered by Fatigue, Fever, GI, and Respiratory.

Time-wise Correlation Analysis¶

For each of our sensorized indicators, we compute time-wise correlations over a moving window of 6 weeks wide. For each six-week window and each county, we compute the Spearman rank correlation with smoothed case incidence data from USA-Facts. Notice that for a 6-week window ending with date t, the data considered are sensorized by static sensorization which is trained on data from the earliest date (2020-02-20) to date t-7. This means the data we used for different time windows have different "as of date". On the contrary, the target we use is the smoothed confirm case incidence rates provided by USA-Facts with as of date 2020-12-14.

In the line plots below, we show the median (solid lines) and 0.25 & 0.75 quantiles (filled area) of the correlations for each across all available counties for that indicator. Recall that the list of available counties for different indicators can vary largely. This can help explain why the lines for Sensory have stronger fluctuations. In general, Sensory shows the best time-wise correlation against the target. As for the methods for dealing with missingness, filling 0 or using fillminratio method, which is a little bit more complicated as described above, does not make much difference which indicates us it's reasonable to just fill missing dates with 0. Comparatively, combining multiple symptoms within a symptom set using regression is better than simply computing the raw sum, but the benefit is not substantial. Regression is 1.5-2 times more computationally expansive than the raw sum which should not be prohibitive.

plt.figure(figsize = (18, 24))
i=1
color_dict = {("fill0", "rawsum"): "blue",
              ("fill0", "regression"): "yellow",
              ("fillminratio", "rawsum"): "green",
              ("fillminratio", "regression"): "red"}

signal_list = ["Fatigue", "Fever", "GI", "Sensory", "Respiratory", "Pain", "Combined"]
corr_dfs = {}
for signal in signal_list:
    plt.subplot(7, 2, i)
    i+=1
    for fillmissingness in ["fill0", "fillminratio"]:
        corr_dfs[fillmissingness] = {}
        for method in ["rawsum", "regression"]:
            corr_dfs[fillmissingness][method] = {}
                    
            corr_dfs[fillmissingness][method][signal] = pd.read_csv("./sensorization_with_as_of_02/time_wise_corr/%s_corr_df_%s_%s.csv"%(signal,
                                                                                            method,
                                                                                            fillmissingness),
                                                                   parse_dates=["date"]) 
            corr_dfs[fillmissingness][method][signal]["county"] = [str(x).zfill(5) for x in corr_dfs[fillmissingness][method][signal]["county"]]

            current_df = corr_dfs[fillmissingness][method][signal]
            plot_df = current_df.groupby("date")["correlation"].median().reset_index()
            plot_75_df = current_df.groupby("date")["correlation"].quantile(0.75).reset_index()
            plot_25_df = current_df.groupby("date")["correlation"].quantile(0.25).reset_index()
            plt.plot(plot_df["date"], plot_df["correlation"], label="%s & %s"%(method, fillmissingness),
                    color = color_dict[(fillmissingness, method)])
            plt.fill_between(plot_df["date"], plot_75_df["correlation"], 
                             plot_25_df["correlation"],
                             color=color_dict[(fillmissingness, method)], alpha=0.1,
                             interpolate=True)          
            plt.title("%s: Time-wise spearman correlation"%signal, fontsize=18)
            plt.ylim((-1, 1))
            plt.xlabel("Date", fontsize=13)
            plt.ylabel("Correlation", fontsize=13)
            plt.axhline(0, linestyle="--")
            plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
            plt.legend()

plt.tight_layout()

Geo-wise Correlation Analysis¶

Remember that the raw dataset is scaled in a regionally specific manner which makes it incomparable across locations. A benefit of sensorization is that now it makes sense to consider the geo-wise correlation of the indicators based on Google-symptoms. On the plots shown below, each point of a single line represents the geo-wise correlation against the target with as of date 2020-12-14, but the data of the sensorized indicator has as of date equal to the current date. For example, for the point at date t, the data we used for the Fatigue indicator is predicted by linear regression models trained on data from the earliest date 2020-02-20 to date t-7 for each county.

Again, the lists of locations considered when calculating the geo-wise correlation for different indicators are different for different symptom sets. This could explain why sensory stands out with stronger fluctuation. There are only ~100 counties considered for sensory but >1400 counties considered for other indicators. As with the time-wise correlation analysis, the method for filling missingness does not make a big influence. Besides, regression slightly outperforms rawsum for combining multiple symptoms.

Coefficients and Intercepts (consider fill0 only)¶

For rawsum¶

Before using the blend of static sensorization, we combine the values for symptoms within a specific symptom set by taking the rawsum. As introduced in the report, for each date t and each location c, we train the linear regression model based on data from the first date (2020-02-20) to 7 days ago (date t-7). And the coefficients and intercepts returned by the linear regression model are labeled as parameters for date t and location c. Notice that the list of available counties is different for each symptom set.

Remember the Google symptoms values are pre-scaled according to a regionally specific population of search users and the maximum value of the normalized popularity overall symptoms. The rawsum values will be dominated by symptoms with the largest overall popularity which can be seen from the plots below. The plot on the left shows the median of the raw trend of rawsum for different symptom sets. Notice that the list of available counties is different for different symptom sets. The curves in the right plot are scaled by the maximum popularity of the rawsum for each symptom sets. Peoples search enthusiasm for fever and cough reached an unusually high point at the first peak of COVID-19 which is never approached later. The overall trends of Fever and Respiratory are much different from others.

A big difference between Google symptoms search trend and cases/deaths related dataset is that the former one is affected by people's emotions and habits while the latter one is not. From the search trend of Fever and Respiratory (rawsum values, dominated by fever and cough respectively), we can see that when first learned about the relationship between COVID-19 and common symptoms such as fever and cough, a lot of search behaviors occurred in mid-March which is largely caused by media propaganda. As time goes by, the search behavior usually comes from medical staff and people who have related symptoms themselves or people around them. From then on, the datasets become more "stable" and can serve as indicators similarly to what we have already like Facebook %CLI. This phenomenon leads to negative coefficients for Fever and Respiratory which is definitely problematic since important fluctuation after April won't get the attention it deserves. One solution to this is to change the start date from 2020-02-20 to a date that is at the end of the first wave. Another potential solution is to use a convolutional model instead of a simple linear regression model so as to put different weights on time series values.

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
plt.figure(figsize = (18, 18))
i=1
signal_list = ["Fatigue", "Fever", "GI", "Sensory", "Respiratory", "Pain", "Combined"]
for signal in signal_list:
    # Read sensorization result
    df = pd.read_csv("./sensorization_with_as_of_02/sensored/%s_rawsum_fill0_sensorization_12_14.csv"%signal,
                    parse_dates=["date"])
    df = df.loc[df["date"] >= datetime(2020, 4, 15)]
    num_geo_list = df["geo_id"].unique().shape[0]
    median_df = df.groupby("date").median().reset_index().drop(["geo_id"], axis=1)
    mad_df = df.groupby("date").mad().reset_index().drop(["geo_id"], axis=1)
    summary_df = median_df.merge(mad_df, on="date", suffixes=["_median", "_mad"])
    
    plt.subplot(7, 2, i)
    plt.plot(summary_df["date"], summary_df["coef_median"], color = "red", label="median of coefficients")
    plt.plot(summary_df["date"], summary_df["coef_median"] + summary_df["coef_mad"], 
             color = "red", linestyle = "--")
    plt.plot(summary_df["date"], summary_df["coef_median"] - summary_df["coef_mad"], 
             color = "red", label="median +/- mad", linestyle = "--")
    plt.title("%s: Coefficents from sensorization with rawsum\
    \nMedians and MADs taken across %d counties"%(signal, num_geo_list), fontsize=18)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Coefficient")
    
    plt.subplot(7, 2, i+1)
    plt.plot(summary_df["date"], summary_df["intercept_median"], color = "black", label="median of intercepts")
    plt.plot(summary_df["date"], summary_df["intercept_median"] + summary_df["intercept_mad"], 
             color = "black", linestyle = "--")
    plt.plot(summary_df["date"], summary_df["intercept_median"] - summary_df["intercept_mad"], 
             color = "black", label="median +/- mad", linestyle = "--")
    plt.title("%s: Intercepts from sensorization with rawsum\
              \nMedians and MADs taken across %d counties"%(signal, num_geo_list), fontsize=18)
    plt.axhline(0, linestyle = "--", color = "white")
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Intercept")
    i+=2
plt.tight_layout()

For regression¶

Different from rawsum, here we combine the values for symptoms within a specific symptom sets by considering them as different features when training linear regression model. The coefficients and intercepts returned by the linear regression model, which is trained based on data in location c from the first date (2020-02-20) to 7 days ago (date t-7), are labeled as parameters for date t and location c. The same, the list of available counties are different for different symptom sets.

The violin plot shown above and the barplot shown in Appendix II indicate the difference in the spatial distribution of symptoms in the same symptom set. This leads to the fact that when training linear regression models for different counties, the number of features (symptoms) that are "actually" taken into account is different. If we draw the median of coefficients for symptoms across all the counties available for the symptom set, we simply get 0s for symptoms with low geographical coverage. It should be noted that getting median to zero is not an error message, because the default missingness of this data set is caused by the extremely low search volume and will be filled with 0s or other small values using fillminratio method.

However, we are more interested in the stories that happened in the shared counties. From the plots shown below, we can see that the signs of coefficients can be different which probably implies the lag in time between the search behavior and the confirmation of new COVID cases can vary largely between symptoms in the same symptom sets. Compared with the rawsum model, the regression model can deal with this problem to some extent.

# Filter out counties with more than 50% days unavailable
SYMPTOM_COUNTY_SET = {}
gs_df = pd.read_csv("./raw/county_google_symptoms_allcovid_12_14.csv", parse_dates=["date"])
n_days = (gs_df["date"].max() - gs_df["date"].min()).days + 1

gs_df = gs_df[~gs_df["geo_id"].isnull()]
gs_df["geo_id"] = [str(int(x)).zfill(5) for x in gs_df["geo_id"]]

for idx in range(2, gs_df.columns.shape[0]):
    symptom = gs_df.columns[idx].split(":")[1]
    subdf = gs_df[[gs_df.columns[idx], "geo_id", "date"]].dropna()
    subdf.loc[subdf[gs_df.columns[idx]] == 0, gs_df.columns[idx]] = np.nan
    mask_df = subdf.groupby("geo_id").count()

    geo_list = set(mask_df[mask_df[gs_df.columns[idx]] >= n_days*0.5].index.values)

    SYMPTOM_COUNTY_SET[gs_df.columns[idx]] = geo_list

Predictive Power Analysis¶

For each indicator, we evaluate its predictive power against confirmed case incidence rates provided by USA-Facts following the instruction of Ryans forecasting notebook and use data for dates from 2020-09-01 to 2020-12-08. We perform forecasts for 5 days ahead through 20 days ahead. For each comparison, the number of counties considered remains the same for each indicator. For example, Sensory has only 109 counties available. The predictive power for Doctor Visits and Facebook %CLI is also calculated based on data for those counties only. Since Facebook %CLI is only available for ~1k counties while Pain has data for >2k counties, we only use Doctor Visits for that comparison. Therefore, the number of counties considered for each subplot is different but is the same for different indicators within a subplot.

Notice that we take as_of date into consideration when conducting the correlation analysis and we assume that there is a 5-day lag in the Google Symptoms dataset which is not the reality. In the predictive power analysis, we adopt the main idea from Ryan's forecasting notebook but considers varying as_of date (not using a constant as of date of the DAP but the as of date of each forecast date) when computing the predictive error across time by using 14-day moving windows.

The indicators derived from Sensory symptom sets are competitive as Doctor Visits and Facebook %CLI. The rawsum indicators outperform most of the other indicators though they have extremely poor geographical coverage. Unfortunately, the indicators derived from other symptom sets do not always beat Doctor Visits and Facebook %CLI. They show worse predictive power compared to the case-only model if choosing the target to be 5-15 days ahead.

One interesting finding is that the indicators created via the regression model tend to obtain worse predictive power compared to the indicators created via rawsum model. Together with our analysis of correlation and coefficients, we can find that although we have previously concluded that the regression model has "stronger" adjustment capability when combining multiple symptoms with a large difference in overall popularity and geographic coverage. This adjustment ability is not necessarily helpful for forecasting because it increases the risk of overfitting.

Discussion¶

The blend of static sensorization theoretically and practically makes sense for generating new Google symptom indicators based on multiple COVID-related symptoms. According to the analysis and visualization showed above, the choice of methods for filling missing dates does not matter much. We can simply fill in missing dates with 0s.

Using regression in the sensorization training step is a better way to combine multiple symptoms because it takes the lag in time between search behavior and the confirmation of COVID cases into consideration by adjusting the sign of coefficients. Besides, since the geographical coverage can be extremely different for symptoms in the same symptom set, the rawsum values are always dominated by symptoms with large overall popularity and better geographical coverage which makes the rest of the symptoms useless. Comparatively, since we do a min-max scaling before training the regression model, the overall popularity for all the symptoms is scaled to the same level and the coefficients returned by sensorization are also helpful now to understand the contribution made by different symptoms. However, the regression model can be much more computationally costly when taking a large number of symptoms into consideration (e.g. ~60 symptoms for the combined indicator) and it also largely increases the risk of overfitting.

Though the indicators for different symptom sets have very different geographical coverage, they show good time-wise and geo-wise correlation against the smoothed confirmed case incidence rates (from USA-Facts) and not too bad predictive power. But to make this dataset more useful to our forecasting work, a more complicated model is needed to take the lag in time considered for different symptoms.

The DAP is finished when the dataset is not updated by Google daily, we didn't talk anything about the backfill problem for the dataset. All the data we used is based on the dataset updated on 2020-12-14.
